> Pork tenderloin is one of our favorite cuts because it's lean, juicy, and impeccably tender. Its flavor is on the mild side, so this recipe dresses it up with a glaze equal parts savory, sweet, and piquant from the mix of soy sauce, honey, and mustard, then rounds it out with roasted veggies.

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Bring @water{2 3/4%cups} and @salt{pinch} to a boil in a #medium pot{}. Core, seed, and remove white ribs from @red bell pepper{2}. Thinly slice crosswise. Peel and thinly slice @carrots{2} into rounds. Cut white and light green parts of @scallions{4} into 2-inch pieces. Set scallion greens aside. Trim @snow peas{16%oz}.

Once water is boiling, add @basmati rice{1 1/2%cups} to #pot{}. Cover and reduce to a simmer. Cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Remove from heat and keep covered.

Meanwhile, toss carrots, bell peppers, snow peas, and scallion pieces with a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{4%tsp} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} on a #baking sheet{}. Roast until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season @pork tenderloin{24%oz} all over with salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook until nicely browned, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. Transfer to baking sheet with veggies. Roast until cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}.

While pork and veggies roast, stir together @soy sauce{1.5%oz}, @honey{1.5%oz}, and @dijon mustard{1} in pan you cooked pork in and bring to a simmer over medium heat. Cook until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Let pork rest ~{5%minutes} after removing from oven. Thinly slice scallion greens.

Thinly slice pork. Divide rice between plates and top with veggies, pork, and glaze. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.